  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 7c09c127496492f4d869cfe59c2fafa3, type: 3}
    _text: In 1534, the order of the Society of Jesus was founded in Spain to spread
      the Catholic faith and European customs to the native people of South America.
  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: f931ab8799bba384faed31a3f164a6d1, type: 3}
    _text: In the so-called "reductions", the Jesuits gathered the Indians to work
      in the countryside and in craft and educational activities.
  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: b55f9683144dddd41975f5cb65f93e44, type: 3}
    _text: In 1750, Portugal and Spain signed the Treaty of Madrid, which transferred
      Portugal's Colonia de Sacramento to Spain, in exchange for the Seven Reductions
      east of the Uruguay River that was inhabited by more than 30,000 Guarani people.
  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: b55f9683144dddd41975f5cb65f93e44, type: 3}
    _text: Given six months to evacuate the territory, the Guarani people refused
      the idea of leaving the mission settlements and decided to stay at their land.
  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 4624df3c935579c41b0808e87b205311, type: 3}
    _text: Most of the Jesuits and Guarani evacuated the missions and headed to the
      other side of the river. However, though a pacific people, some Guarani leaders
      formed resistance groups to defend their land and their right to stay there.
  - _image: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 4624df3c935579c41b0808e87b205311, type: 3}
    _text: "This resistance later turned into what is known today as the Guaranitic
      War\u2026"
